  "prompt": "Why does the Justin Bieber video Baby have more dislikes than likes?",
  "response": "The disparity between likes and dislikes on Justin Bieber's \"Baby\" video can be attributed to several factors:\n\n1. **Cultural Backlash**: When the song was released, Justin Bieber was a young pop star with a dedicated fanbase, but his music also attracted significant criticism from those who didn't enjoy his style or genre. This backlash can lead to a higher number of dislikes.\n\n2. **Viral Nature**: The song became a massive hit, leading to a large number of views, including from people who might not be fans. Many viewers might have been inclined to dislike the video simply to express their opinions or as a form of trolling.\n\n3. **Demographics of Viewers**: The target audience for \"Baby\" primarily consisted of younger fans, while older viewers or those outside the pop genre might have had a different perspective and chosen to express their dislike.\n\n4. **Longevity and Trends**: Over time, as social media and public opinions evolve, some videos can accumulate dislikes as viewers reflect on the content differently or as trends shift.\n\n5. **Engagement and Social Media Influence**: Certain internet communities may rally around disliking popular content, which can lead to a spike in dislikes as more people feel encouraged to join in.\n\nOverall, the reasons are multifaceted, combining elements of popularity, cultural dynamics, and user engagement factors.",
